## How Soil Moisture Detection WorksMost hobbyist soil moisture systems use a resistive soil moisture sensor.
The Principle: The sensor consists of two exposed probes. Water conducts electricity; dry soil does not.
The Math: When the soil is wet, the resistance between the probes drops, allowing more current to pass.
This increases the voltage read by the analog pin (A_0).
When the soil is dry, the resistance increases, and the analog voltage drops.
The Calibration: The raw values from an Arduino analog pin range from 0 to 1023. 
Because sensors vary, we use the map() function to convert these arbitrary raw numbers into a user-friendly percentage (0\% to 100\%)

### Hardware Wiring Components
Connect your sensor to the Arduino using this pin layout:
Soil Sensor     PinArduino       PinDescription
VCC             5V or 3.3V       Power input
GND             GND              Ground reference 
AO (Analog Out) A0               Sends the variable voltage to the Arduino
DO (Digital Out)                 Leave DisconnectedNot needed (used for a simple high/low threshold)

### Complete, Presentation-Ready Code
This code reads the analog values, converts them to a percentage, and outputs the status to the Serial Monitor. 
It includes smooth calibration boundaries.

// --- Sujay's Soil Moisture Detection Node ---

const int SOIL_PIN = A0;  // Analog pin connected to the sensor AO

// Calibration values (Adjust these if your sensor readings feel inverted)
// Standard resistive sensors read ~1023 in completely dry air and ~200 fully submerged in water.
const int DRY_VALUE = 1023; 
const int WET_VALUE = 200;  

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(9600); // Standard serial baud rate
  pinMode(SOIL_PIN, INPUT);
  
  Serial.println("\n=====================================");
  Serial.println("  ARECA EYE: SOIL MOISTURE NODE ACTIVE ");
  Serial.println("=====================================");
}

void loop() {
  // 1. Read the raw analog value (0 to 1023)
  int rawValue = analogRead(SOIL_PIN);

  // 2. Map the raw value to a percentage (0% to 100%)
  // We place DRY_VALUE first because higher voltage often means drier soil on these boards.
  int moisturePercent = map(rawValue, DRY_VALUE, WET_VALUE, 0, 100);

  // 3. Constrain the percentage between 0% and 100% to handle extreme spikes
  moisturePercent = constrain(moisturePercent, 0, 100);

  // 4. Determine field condition status
  String condition = "";
  if (moisturePercent < 30) {
    condition = "CRITICAL: DRY SOIL (Needs Irrigation)";
  } else if (moisturePercent > 80) {
    condition = "ALERT: OVERWATERED (Risk of Root Rot)";
  } else {
    condition = "OPTIMAL: IDEAL MOISTURE";
  }

  // 5. Print out the structured data for presentation
  Serial.print("Raw Signal: ");
  Serial.print(rawValue);
  Serial.print("  |  Moisture Level: ");
  Serial.print(moisturePercent);
  Serial.print("%  |  Status: ");
  Serial.println(condition);

  delay(1500); // Stable 1.5 second refresh rate
}
